<dl id="n03038d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n03" href="#n03038d">N03 (VI.B.3)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n03all.htm#n03038d"> 38(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Two Easters in Irel / (R.C &amp; ortho Greek <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n03038d"><li>FW 188.10f </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/lexg.htm#n03038d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/l39g.htm#n03038d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n03038d">MS BL 47471b-66</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:377 <a name="g20d" href="../../ff/fdra/gda.htm#g20d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/g/g20d.htm#n03038d">Draft: I.7&sect;2.0</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">In the controversy which raged around the observance of <mark>Easter</mark>, Ronan <font color="green">[an Irish Scholar]</font> was a zealous defender of the <mark>Roman</mark> view, which had long before been adopted by people in the southern half of Ireland, but which was strongly opposed by those who clung to the tradition of Columcille. <small> Benedict Fitzpatrick, <a name="BFIM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BFIM"><cite title="source">Ireland and the Making of Britain</cite></a> (1922) 228</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: The two Easters are (1) the date observed by Rome and (2) that observed in Constantinople. </mm> </dd></dl>
